annotation.TEXT: On Dialing for Dollars, a local TV host would announce “the count and the amount” and make a random call: if the person had been watching, they would know the answer and win a cash prize.
Chinese fire drills were a popular prank in the ‘60s, in which everyone in a car at a red light would get out and run around the car before diving back into any available seat.
Coco Chanel was a legendary fashion designer whose company remains a leader in haute couture; the name Chanel is synonymous with expensive, elegant clothing.
The old trope that one feels hungry an hour after eating Chinese food has been around since at least the ‘30s, although research has failed to confirm it.
She has been the subject of outlandish rumors about the plastic surgery she has had done, thanks to her seemingly eternal youth. (She denies them.)
Brie is a soft cow’s-milk cheese named for the area in northern France where it originated.
The slogan from a mid-‘80s TV ad jingle for Tab diet soft drink.
Actress Angie Dickinson has appeared in more than 100 movies and TV shows, including Police Woman and Dressed to Kill.
Hole was an LA alt-rock band founded by Courtney Love and Eric Erlandson.
The incidental music is similar to the famous theme to Jaws, composed by John Williams for the 1975 blockbuster.
Jumble is a scrambled word game that appears in daily newspapers around the country.
The jazz piano piece used in the Peanuts TV specials is called “Linus and Lucy” and was written by Vince Guaraldi.
Pan was a fertility deity in ancient Greek mythology who had the horns and legs of a goat.
Author John Irving is a former wrestler and has worked as a coach. His memoir about his wrestling experiences is called The Imaginary Girlfriend.
The peyote cactus is native to southern Texas and northern Mexico. It has hallucinogenic properties and is used in the ceremonies of some Native American religions.
Lucy Ricardo, as played by Lucille Ball on I Love Lucy, was a bumbling housewife always plotting to horn in on husband Desi Arnaz’s show-biz career.
Reginald Jeeves was the quintessential “gentleman’s gentleman” to the bumbling Bertie Wooster in a long string of books by P.G. Wodehouse.
A paraphrase of the world-famous line from The Graduate, spoken by Dustin Hoffman to the leggy Anne Bancroft: “Mrs. Robinson, you’re trying to seduce me.”
In 2015, a judge ruled the copyright claims to “Happy Birthday” invalid; companies had been collecting royalties on it for 80 years.
In A Night at the Opera, the Marx Brothers stow away on a ship and steal the uniforms (and beards) of three famed aviators to use as disguises.
Giorgio was the first perfume to advertise with a “scent strip” included in a magazine (Vogue, in this case).
As always, let us know in the comments if we missed any references!
Carlton was the unseen doorman to Rhoda’s apartment building on the sitcom Rhoda; he was played by veteran voiceover actor Lorenzo Music.
The World Wrestling Federation was forced to change their name to World Wrestling Entertainment after losing a lawsuit with the World Wildlife Fund.
Vaseline is a brand of petroleum jelly; while it is normally used on the skin, the company also makes a hair tonic.
A reference to the various cars (usually pink) driven by Barbie dolls; the Malibu Barbie was released in 1971.
The phrase “Kill ‘em all and let God sort ‘em out” dates to a version attributed to Catholic papal legate and inquisitor Arnaud Amalric in 1209.
A more elaborate variation of the popular slumber-party game Truth or Dare.
A line from the Beatles song “A Day in the Life.”
An imitation of Gladys Kravitz, the nosy neighbor on the TV show Bewitched; her husband’s name was Abner.
In 1488 Portuguese explorer Bartolomeu Dias became the first European to sail around the Cape of Good Hope and open a sea route to Asia.
In the ‘90s, Stuart Anderson’s Cattle Company was a chain of steakhouses found around the country.
Strauss’s father was also a famous composer, known primarily for the “Radetzky March.”
Red Wing, Minnesota, is a small city on the Mississippi River, population 16,000. It is home to Red Wing Shoes and Red Wing Stoneware.
“Come to the dark side” is a reference to the Star Wars trilogy, although Darth Vader never actually uses that phrase in urging Luke Skywalker to join him.
We hope you enjoyed the fully-annotated Samson vs. the Vampire Women!
Martha Stewart is an author, TV host, and entrepreneur whose business is centered on beautiful living and domesticity.
A line from the song “Rhiannon” by Fleetwood Mac.
The first ever Academy Awards were handed out at the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel in 1929, with Douglas Fairbanks hosting. The ceremony lasted 15 minutes.
A Magic Eye picture is an autostereogram: a 3D image embedded in a seemingly random assortment of patterns. They became very popular in the early ‘90s.
HUD homes were bought with a HUD-insured mortgage and defaulted on. HUD (Housing & Urban Development) then forecloses and sells the home.
“Imperialist running dog” is an insult originating from communist China, similar to calling someone a lapdog begging for scraps.
Bela Lugosi’s most famous role is of course Count Dracula, which he played on Broadway before appearing in the classic 1931 film.
The International Male catalog peddled incredibly campy men’s clothing for more than 30 years. We’re talking gold lamé ties and fishnet T-shirts.
Thorazine is an antipsychotic drug used to treat people suffering from schizophrenia.
Reddy Kilowatt is a small anthropomorphic lightning bolt, created in 1926 as an ad icon for the Alabama Power Company.
A Black Russian is a cocktail consisting of vodka and coffee-flavored liqueur, such as Kahlua, served over ice.
Goodfellas is a Martin Scorsese film about three mobsters working their way up through the ranks of the Mafia.
“Biffy” is slang in the Upper Midwest for an outdoor toilet.
Wall Drug is a pharmacy/tourist trap in the tiny town of Wall, South Dakota. For years it blanketed the nation’s highways with signs to lure in motorists.
Little Women is a beloved children’s book by Louisa May Alcott. More than 10 filmed versions have been made; the most famous is the 1933 one starring Katharine Hepburn.
An ad from the ‘70s starring Polish actress Rula Lenska used the line “Friends from Europe are here,” later parodied by Jambi on the Pee-wee Herman HBO special.
The “Family Circus” comic strip sometimes publishes crudely drawn cartoons, claiming they were done by “Billy,” the strip’s 7-year-old son.
In 1519, Spanish conquistador Hernán Cortés and 500 men arrived in Mexico. They captured the Aztec emperor Montezuma and laid siege to the capital; by 1521 they had conquered the empire.
Baptists and Catholics haven’t really gotten along; one reason is Mass, which Baptists find blasphemous, both for the “body and blood” of communion and for the “idols” of saints in churches.
Larry Tate was Darrin Stephens’ neurotic boss on the TV show Bewitched; he was played by David White.
Walker, Texas Ranger was a TV series starring martial artist Chuck Norris as a Texas lawman who kicked and punched crime into submission.
Henry Kissinger was Secretary of State under Richard Nixon and Gerald Ford and was one of the major architects of Nixon’s Vietnam War policy.
If we somehow missed one, let us know in the comments!
Ginger Rogers was a singer/dancer/actress often paired with Fred Astaire in such films as Flying Down to Rio and Top Hat.
Darrin Stephens was played first by Dick York and later by Dick Sargent.
“Hi-yo, Silver, awaaay!” is the classic catchphrase of the Lone Ranger, portrayed most famously by actor Clayton Moore.
Singer/actress Cher was born in 1946 under the name Cherilyn Sarkisian.
This was a running gag in a series of short cartoons about race driver Tom Slick in the ‘60s animated series George of the Jungle.
“Mug Clubs” are programs at bars and restaurants that provide a custom mug to patrons, with which they can drink beer at a discounted price.
A G-rated version of a line from the film Full Metal Jacket: “Drop your cocks and grab your socks.”
The media coined “wilding” in 1989 after a gang of teenagers allegedly raped and beat a young female jogger in Central Park. DNA evidence exonerated them in 2002 after years in prison.
Strauss the Younger’s other big hit was the operetta Die Fledermaus.
A line from the song “You’re a Mean One, Mr. Grinch” from the classic animated Christmas special How the Grinch Stole Christmas!
In CB (Citizens Band) radio slang, popular in the ‘70s, a handle was a nickname adopted by a CB user.
Jeremiah Johnson is a film starring Robert Redford as a reclusive, fur-clad mountain man.
Sturgis, a small town in the Black Hills of South Dakota, hosts an annual biker rally every August that draws more than half a million people.
A callback to Episode 201, Rocketship X-M.
A joke from the 1977 Woody Allen film Annie Hall.
This is the theme to the TV series Batman, which was composed by Neal Hefti.
Founded in 1948, Wham-O is the company behind such classic toys as the Frisbee, the Super Ball, and the hula hoop.
A take on the old ad slogan for Trident chewing gum: “Who wants Trident? I do! I do!”
And now…the fully-annotated Samson vs. the Vampire Women!
The Dutch Masters were a group of painters from the Netherlands in the 17th century, including Vermeer, Hals, and Rembrandt.
Pond's is a brand of cold cream used as a facial cleanser.
The Rainforest Cafe is a theme restaurant whose ersatz trees and recorded nature sounds can be found in concrete and glass shopping malls in several countries, including the US.
Possibly an imitation of George C. Scott as General George S. Patton in the film Patton. In real life, Patton’s voice was high-pitched and nasal.
Martha Graham was an influential dancer and choreographer who founded the Martha Graham Dance Company in 1926, which still performs.
Actress Phyllis Newman was a well-known panelist on game shows in the ‘60s & ‘70s, appearing on What’s My Line?, Match Game, and To Tell the Truth.
“Making the beast with two backs” is a slang term for sexual intercourse; it first appears in Rabelais’ Gargantua and Pantagruel: la bête à deux dos.
Garth Hudson was the keyboardist for The Band and has also played with John Hammond Jr. and Bob Dylan, among many others.
That was Maybelline’s ad slogan from the ‘60s to the ‘80s.
The How and Why Wonder Books was a series of children’s reference books in the ‘60s and ‘70s focusing on science and history.
Naomi and Wynonna Judd were a mother/daughter country-western duo whose hits include “Love Can Build a Bridge” and “I Saw the Light.”
The Flying Karamazov Brothers are a troupe of jugglers named after the Dostoyevsky novel The Brothers Karamazov.
The Keystone Kops were a group of wildly incompetent policemen in a series of short silent films for Mack Sennett’s Keystone Film Co. from 1912-17.
Disclosure is a 1994 movie about a man (Michael Douglas) who is sexually harassed by his female boss/ex-girlfriend (Demi Moore).
Comedian Jackie Mason has had a string of successful one-man shows on Broadway.
Basically the plot of the 1984 James Cameron film The Terminator.
Robert Mapplethorpe was an American photographer known for his homoerotic photos of nude men.
The wooded Ardennes in northern Europe was the location of horrific battles during WWI and WWII.
Seinfeld was a sitcom starring comedian Jerry Seinfeld that became one of the country’s top-rated shows during its 9-year run.
An imitation of Bruce Wayne’s butler Alfred from the ‘60s TV show Batman, as portrayed by Alan Napier.
G. Gordon Liddy was the leader of the Watergate burglars in the scandal that brought down President Richard Nixon.
Andersen Corp. makes doors and windows; its headquarters are in a suburb of St. Paul, Minnesota.
Mickey Spillane wrote hard-boiled detective novels starring Mike Hammer, a hard-drinking, hard-fighting, quick-shooting private eye.
Longtime radio broadcaster Paul Harvey was known for narrating the turn of a page and ending his broadcast with “Good day!”
A line from the song “Ten Minutes Ago,” written by Rodgers & Hammerstein for a TV production of Cinderella starring Julie Andrews.
Joan Embery, as the longtime goodwill ambassador for the San Diego Zoo, appeared on many talk shows, along with various zoo critters.
An imitation of veteran sportscaster Howard Cosell, who was the commentator on the TV show Monday Night Football from 1970-83.
Jokes about the stupidity of Poles became popular in the ‘60s & ‘70s; the first Polish joke books were compiled by the Polish-Jewish Larry Wilde.
Republican Newt Gingrich, Speaker of the House in the ‘90s, once proposed taking the children of single mothers on welfare away and placing them in orphanages.
Movietone News were weekly newsreels shown in movie theaters before the feature. The March of Time was a newsreel that combined news footage with “dramatic reenactments.”
A parody of the song “On the Street Where You Live,” from the musical My Fair Lady.
Rush Limbaugh helped lead the conservative talk radio revolution in the ‘90s. He is not what you would call a thin man.
“What you choose to call hell, he calls home” is a line from the Sylvester Stallone film Rambo: First Blood Part II.
A Tom Collins is a cocktail made with gin, lemon juice, sugar, and club soda and garnished with a lemon slice and a cherry.
Princess Kay of the Milky Way is a Minnesota beauty queen crowned by the Midwest Dairy Association. The lucky winner gets her likeness sculpted in 90 lbs. of butter at the state fair.
Samson vs. the Vampire Women: Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Country singer Barbara Mandrell had a TV variety show with sisters Louise and Irlene from 1980-82: Barbara Mandrell and the Mandrell Sisters.
Bachelor Father was a sitcom starring John Forsythe as a bachelor who finds himself in charge of his teenage niece Kelly.
German Max Schmeling fought two bouts with American Joe Louis. He won the first in 1936; Louis won the 1938 rematch in the first round, a symbolic victory for democracy over Nazism.
The Ford Escort model debuted in the US in 1981 and sold well throughout the ‘80s and ‘90s.
Capitol Critters was an animated TV show about a group of animals that lived in the walls of the White House.
Cher first rose to fame as part of a duo with her then-husband Sonny Bono; the two hosted a TV variety show in the ‘70s.
The phrase “up, up, and away!” originated on the ‘40s Superman radio show, to indicate to listeners when the Man of Steel had taken flight.
A line from the Sade song of the same name.
Delta Burke is best known for playing Suzanne Sugarbaker on the TV series Designing Women.
Billionaire playboy Bruce Wayne, a.k.a. Batman, has a loyal butler named Alfred Pennyworth.
Strauss the Younger also had two composer brothers: Josef and Eduard.
A reference to the 1968 film Where Angels Go, Trouble Follows.
Fantasy Grams appears to be a singing telegram service in Minneapolis.
A series of ads for Shell gasoline back in the ‘60s bragged about its mysterious ingredient, Platformate, that dramatically improved engine performance.
An imitation of Gregory Peck as Atticus Finch in the film version of To Kill a Mockingbird. Scout is the nickname of Finch’s daughter.
Cream of Wheat is a wheat farina porridge that debuted at the 1893 World’s Fair in Chicago.
General Hospital is a TV soap opera that hit its peak of popularity in the ‘80s with the romance between Luke Spencer and Laura Gray Vining Webber Baldwin Spencer Baldwin.
“Macho Man” Randy Savage was a pro wrestler for decades, famous for his raspy voice and his running feud with Hulk Hogan.
The lumberjack on the Brawny paper towel package has been given a makeover several times since the brand was introduced in the ‘70s.
Lee Press-on Nails—artificial nails with an adhesive backing—were advertised constantly on TV during the ‘80s.
In 18th-century England, there was a real Riot Act, and authorities had to actually read a proclamation from it, out loud, before they could order crowds to disperse.
White Castle is a chain of fast food burger restaurants that sells tiny square burgers.
Cage matches are pro wrestling matches that surround the ring with a barrier, usually chain-link fencing. Sometimes, for extra fun, the cage is electrified.
The schottische is a ballroom dance that became popular in Europe around 1850, similar to a slow polka.
Pepsi, originally marketed in 1893 as Brad’s Drink, is the chief rival to Coca-Cola.
A common prompt used in classroom filmstrips.
The Oak Ridge Boys are a country-music band with longish hair. William Lee Golden in particular has had an increasingly majestic beard over the years.
Mothra was a Japanese monster movie about a giant moth that levels Tokyo.
Comedian and actor Andy Kaufman used a wrestling act in his performances for years; he often wrestled women, including Playboy centerfold Susan Smith.
Actress Suzanne Pleshette appeared in more than 50 movies and TV shows, including The Birds and The Bob Newhart Show.
Lillian Hellman was a playwright and screenwriter whose best-known works include The Children’s Hour and The Little Foxes.
Child actor Butch Patrick played werewolf Eddie Munster on the ‘60s TV series The Munsters.
The Quiet Man is a John Ford film starring John Wayne as a boxer who returns to Ireland to reclaim his family’s homestead.
A take on a line from the Prince song “1999.”
Vincent Price’s distinctive voice and lanky frame graced such B-movies as House of Wax, The Fly, and Pit and the Pendulum.
James Michener was an author known for massive novels, including Hawaii (c. 900 pages) and Texas (c. 1,300 pages).
Swiss chocolatier Theodor Tobler was inspired to create his famous triangular bar after seeing dancers form a pyramid at the Folies Bergères in Paris.
Joe Cocker was a British rock & blues singer known for his random full-body spasms onstage.
Comedian Tim Allen is best known for playing Tim Taylor on the TV sitcom Home Improvement.
“I’m waiting for that click” is what Brick says to Maggie in the Tennessee Williams play Cat on a Hot Tin Roof. The film version starred Elizabeth Taylor and Paul Newman.
Nosferatu is a silent film from Germany starring Max Schreck as the Dracula-esque Count Orlok.
In 1917, three children in Fatima, Portugal, reported receiving repeated visitations from the Virgin Mary, dubbed Our Lady of Fatima.
Circus of the Stars was an annual TV special from 1977-94, featuring actors performing traditional circus acts.
Dig in as we explain every reference in the movie.
Be sure to leave a comment if we missed a reference!
Actress/singer Anna Maria Alberghetti started in film and went on to a lengthy stage career, making her Broadway debut in the 1961 musical Carnival.
An imitation of Bob Denver as Gilligan on the sitcom Gilligan’s Island.
Brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
A parody of the Percy Sledge song “When a Man Loves a Woman.”
Johann Strauss the Younger was an Austrian composer known for his waltzes, of which “The Blue Danube,” playing here, is the most famous.
A line from the song “Oh, What a Beautiful Mornin’” from the Rodgers & Hammerstein musical Oklahoma!
A paraphrase of the ABBA song “Fernando”: “Can you hear the drums, Fernando?”
Liberace was a flamboyant entertainer known for elaborate costumes, candelabra, and performances on his custom grand piano.
Actress Thelma Ritter’s best-known role was probably as the outspoken nurse in Alfred Hitchcock’s classic thriller Rear Window.
Legendary boxing promoter Don King managed 7 of Muhammad Ali’s title bouts and has also worked with George Foreman, Larry Holmes, and Mike Tyson.
Death Race 2000 is a 1975 film about a brutal cross-country road race; it starred David Carradine and an unknown Sylvester Stallone, who one year later made Rocky.
In 1994, Orange County, CA, went bankrupt due to its treasurer unwisely investing in extremely risky derivative securities; they lost $1.7 billion.
In Charles Dickens’ Great Expectations, Miss Havisham is a bitter old woman, still clad in her wedding dress, which she has worn since she was jilted years ago.
An ad slogan for Toni, an early brand of home permanent that used pairs of twins in ads—one with a home perm and one with a salon perm.
Nigerian-born singer Sade hit it big in the mid-‘80s with such hits as “Smooth Operator.”
The opening line of Daphne du Maurier’s novel Rebecca, which was made into a film by Alfred Hitchcock, is “Last night I dreamt I went to Manderley again.”
Peter Garrett was lead singer for Australian rock band Midnight Oil for 29 years. ER was a TV drama that launched George Clooney on his career as a Hollywood hunk.
In 1989, brothers Lyle and Erik Menendez killed their parents in their Beverly Hills mansion. They claimed self-defense after years of abuse but were sentenced to life in prison.
Actor Brad Pitt played the aristocratic vampire Louis in the film version of Anne Rice’s Interview with the Vampire.
Freddie de Cordova produced Johnny Carson’s Tonight Show. SCTV parodied his habit of lurking off camera by having “de Cordova” interview his guests unseen while the host’s desk sat empty.
The Cossack tribe became famous in Russia for their military prowess. Also a reference to the sexually and racially charged saying “Once you go black, you never go back.”
The Blue Mosque, one of Istanbul’s most famous landmarks, was built by architect Sedefkar Mehmed Agha for Sultan Ahmed I.
The Minnesota Vikings are a pro football team based in Minneapolis.
An imitation of John Hurt in the film The Elephant Man, based on the true story of a severely deformed man in the 19th century.
Combos are hollowed-out crackers containing various flavors of soft fillings, including cheddar cheese and pepperoni pizza.
A parody of an old ad jingle sung most famously by Dinah Shore: “See the USA/In your Chevrolet …”
The Grateful Dead was a famed rock band from the heyday of the ‘60s. Two of their better-known songs are “Pride of Cucamonga” and “Sugar Magnolia.”
Butterfield 8 is a film starring Elizabeth Taylor as a woman who gets romantically involved with an unhappily married lawyer.
Count Basie was a jazz pianist who led a big band orchestra almost continuously for 50 years. “One more time!” is from April in Paris, one of Basie’s signature songs.
A line from the 1978 song “Who Are You” by, naturally, The Who.
A line from the song “Colour My World” by Chicago.
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
A parody of the old philosophy question: “If a tree falls in the forest and there’s no one to hear it, does it make a sound?”
Comedian Phyllis Diller often made jokes about her fictitious husband “Fang,” a character who she said had to be “even more idiotic than I.”
Little Chute is a small town on the Fox River in Wisconsin, about halfway between Green Bay and Oshkosh. Population: 10,000.
Pop singer Cyndi Lauper was briefly involved in pro wrestling in the mid-‘80s, acting as “manager”/sidekick to wrestler Wendi Richter.
However, Ferdinand was the Spanish king who sponsored Christopher Columbus’ expedition to the New World in 1492.
A paraphrased line from the Irving Berlin song “Sisters,” made famous in the film White Christmas.
This is a drinking toast dating back to the ‘30s. A variant: “Look out liver, here it comes!”
The Very Hungry Caterpillar is a children’s book by Eric Carle, who also wrote The Very Busy Spider and The Very Lonely Firefly.
Spartacus was a 1960 film about a slave who leads a revolt against the Romans. A 1991 version restored a deleted scene in which Laurence Olivier tries to seduce Tony Curtis.
Peter Lupus is a bodybuilder and actor, best known for playing Willy Armitage in the Mission: Impossible TV series.
The Dean Martin Show ran from 1965-74 and starred the famous crooner. A recurring segment began with Martin leaping onto accompanist Ken Lane’s piano.
Nora Dunn was a regular cast member on Saturday Night Live from 1985-90.
Funny Cars are souped-up drag racers that can reach speeds of 300 mph in a 1,000-foot race.
Don DeFore played neighbor “Thorny” Thornberry on The Adventures of Ozzie and Harriet from 1952-57.
A parody of the theme song to the Japanese animated show Speed Racer.
Sort of an imitation of Droopy, the jowly little dog from the MGM animated shorts. He was based on Wallace Wimple from Fibber McGee and voiced by the same actor.
Glam rock in the ‘70s was characterized by flamboyant costumes & makeup and over-the-top theatricality. Practitioners included David Bowie and Gary Glitter.
Fitness guru Jake Steinfeld had a TV exercise show in the late ‘80s titled Body by Jake; his exercise equipment is sold under the same name.
A translation of French philosopher René Descartes’ famous statement “Cogito ergo sum.”
Danny DeVito is a diminutive actor and director who came to fame playing irascible dispatcher Louie De Palma on the TV series Taxi.
In 1982 Cosell famously denounced boxing while covering a bout between Larry Holmes and Tex Cobb, threatening to boycott the sport if the referee did not stop the fight.
Allen Ludden hosted the long-running game show Password and was married to Betty White for nearly 20 years.
Gladys Knight & the Pips (backup singers “Bubba” Knight, William Guest, and Edward Patten) was one of the most popular R&B groups of the ‘60s & ‘70s.
“Flying Leathernecks” is the nickname for Marine aviators. Marines wore a leather band around their necks in the 19th century to protect against sword blows.
The Pilobolus Dance Theatre is a dance troupe based in Connecticut. It has toured around the world and appeared on TV and in dance festivals.
Fabian Forte, known as Fabian, was a teen idol during the late ‘50s and ‘60s, singing and acting in films.
The Lawrence Welk Show was a TV variety show featuring skits and musical numbers; host Lawrence Welk led the band for 27 years.
In the Road Runner WB cartoons, the hapless Wile E. Coyote put together various elaborate schemes to catch the speedy Road Runner, all of which failed (painfully).
German composer Ludwig van Beethoven wrote “Moonlight Sonata,” which Diana is playing here, in 1801.
House Party is a film starring hip-hop duo Kid ‘n Play. Christopher “Kid” Reid boasted a towering hi-top fade.
José Eber is one of the most successful and well-known hairstylists in the world. His salon in Beverly Hills attracts dozens of celebrity clients.
This is an old ad slogan for Kingsford charcoal.
In the Archie comic books and animated TV show, Big Ethel Muggs was a tall, gangly girl with a huge crush on Jughead.
